A Variation of Kadane's Algorithm.
```
class Solution{
	public int maxProduct(int[] nums) {
		int pro=1, msf=nums[0];
		int n=nums.length;
		for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
			pro*=nums[i];
			if(pro>msf)
				msf=pro;
			if(pro==0)
				pro=1;
		}
		pro=1;
		for(int i=n-1;i>=0;i--){
			pro*=nums[i];
			if(pro>msf)
				msf=pro;
			if(pro==0)
				pro=1;
		}
		return msf;
	}
}

```

Time `O(N)`
Space `O(1)`

**Why this solution works?**
This solution works because it says that maximum product subarray possible for any array will include either the `0th` index or `(n-1)th` index or both for sure (Not considering 0 values as elements of array as of now). This is because an array will either have even or odd count of negatives.

If array has even count of `-ve` values, Max product will be the entire array.

If array has odd count of `-ve` values say `k`, then `(k-1)` will be even so considering `k-1` negative values will give us max product. Thus, we can consider first `k-1` negatives starting from left side of array or starting from right side of array. Therefore, i said either the  `0th` index or `(n-1)th` index will be part of answer for sure.
Didn't get this? Do a dry run over this approach. Hint:  The `msf` variable will monitor how to consider only `k-1` negative values.

For 0 values as elements of array, we can reset the `pro` variable calculating product to 1 once again. Thus zeroes also get handled.

