# Intuition
- The intuition behind the given code is to traverse the array twice, once from start to end and once from end to start, to find the maximum product subarray.

- The key idea is to keep track of the current product of elements encountered so far during both traversals, and update the maximum product found so far accordingly. In case the current product becomes 0, it is reset to 1 because any further multiplication with 0 will result in a product of 0.

- By traversing the array twice in opposite directions, the code ensures that it explores all possible subarrays that may result in a maximum product. By taking the maximum value obtained from both traversals, the code returns the maximum product subarray.

Overall, the approach used in the code is intuitive and easy to understand, and provides an efficient solution to the maximum product subarray problem.

# Approach
The approach used in this code is to traverse the array twice but in one loop using two pointers - once from start to end, and once from end to start. During both traversals, two variables "pro1" and "pro2" are used to keep track of the current product of elements encountered so far, while another two variables "max1" and "max2" are used to store the maximum product found so far.

For the forward traversal, the code multiplies each element of the array with the current product "pro1" and updates "max1" with the maximum value obtained so far. If the current product "pro1" becomes 0, it is reset to 1 because any further multiplication with 0 will result in a product of 0.

For the backward traversal, the code multiplies each element of the array with the current product "pro2" and updates "max2" with the maximum value obtained so far. If the current product "pro2" becomes 0, it is reset to 1 because any further multiplication with 0 will result in a product of 0.

Finally, the code returns the maximum value of "max1" and "max2" as the answer.

This approach takes O(N) time, where N is the size of the input array, and uses O(1) extra space, making it an efficient solution to the problem.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- **Time complexity:O(n)**
As we are traversing the entire vector for only one time so we have a linear time complexity and that of the size of the vector.

- **Space complexity: O(1)**
As we have only used variables so we have space complexity of O(1)

# C++
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxProduct(vector<int>& nums) 
    {
        int max1=INT_MIN,pro1=1,max2=INT_MIN,pro2=1,s=nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++)
        {
            //traversing from start to end and keeping the record for maximum current_product(pro1) we get till now
            pro1*=nums[i];
            max1=max(pro1,max1);//storing the maximum of current_product and max1 in max1;
            pro1=(pro1==0?1:pro1);// if we get 0 at any moment, we update the current_product(pro1) by 1.

            //traversing from end to start and keeping the record for maximum current_product(pro2) we get till now
            pro2*=nums[s-1-i];
            max2=max(pro2,max2);
            pro2=(pro2==0?1:pro2);// if we get 0 at any moment, we update the current_product(pro2) by 1.
        }
        return max(max1,max2);    
    }
};
```


