Why wrap your head around complicated kadane logic?

Prefix sums are applicable for the majority of product or sum subarray problems.
So whenever you see finding sum or product subarrays that meet a certain criteria, prefix sums should be the first thing that jump to your head. 

This problem is a  bit tricker than maximum sum, but the idea is the same.
We keep a running product, and divide by previous subarrays to maximize our results.

There are 3 cases to note:
1. if the running product is positive we can just be greedy and take the entire running product
2. if the running product is negative, we need to divide by the previous largest negative running product (or the running product that is closest to zero). We do this because we want the subarray to have the highest possible result.
3. if current number is zero, then this is essentially a reset, and we reset all our variables except the max and act as if the array had been bisected.
```
public int maxProduct(int[] nums) {
        int runningProduct = 1;
        int max = nums[0];
        int largestNegative = Integer.MIN_VALUE;

        for (int num: nums) {
            runningProduct *= num;
            max = Math.max(max, runningProduct);
			// reset if zero
            if (num == 0) {
                runningProduct = 1;
                largestNegative = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            }

			// Our product is negative 
            if (runningProduct < 0) {
                if (largestNegative != Integer.MIN_VALUE) {
				// Divide by negative number closest to zero to maximize subarray
                    max = Math.max(max, runningProduct / largestNegative); 
                }
                largestNegative = Math.max(largestNegative, runningProduct);
            }
        }
        return max;
    }
```

