        SubProblem(i): 
					Max[i]: the maximum product of a continuous subarray that ends at i
                    Min[i]: the minimum product of a continuous subarray that ends at i
		Analysis:
				Note that since the subarray ends at i must include the ith element,
				inorder to get the maximum product that ends at i we only has three cases
				case1: the maximum product that ends at i-1 times the ith number
					e.g. 1 2 3 4 5  we have Max[i] = Max[i-1] * nums[i] for all i
				case2: the minimum product that ends at i-1 times the ith number
					e.g. sign changes involves -1 2 3 4 5 -6, we have Max[5] = Min[4] * nums[5]
					(0 index)
				case3: the maximum product is the ith number
					e.g. -1 0 0 1 we have Max[3] = 1
		Combine these three cases we have:
			Base Case:
					Min[0] = nums[0], Max[0] = nums[0]
			Recursive Case:
						Max[i] = max(Min[i-1] * nums[i], nums[i], Max[i-1] * nums[i])
						Min[i] = max(Min[i-1] * nums[i], nums[i], Max[i-1] * nums[i])
			Answer:
					maximum Max[i]
			Time Complexity:
				O(n)
			Space Complexity:
				O(1), by writing Max[i] as Max[i % 2]


```
