# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can easily reach to the solution by finding out the max product from left side and right side of the array.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First, we have to traverse the array from **0th** index till the last index of **nums[]** array and keep on multiplying the **curr** value with the current index value and check whether **curr > max** or not. If **curr > max** then we simply update max as curr. 

if there's an index in the array whose value is 0 then the curr value gets updated to 1 **(as after that curr value will remain as 0 till the end if we do not update it)**.


Similarly, we traverse from the last index and apply the same logic again.

We do this because, 

for nums[] = [3,-1,4] , if we traverse from left index only then we get the max value as **3**. 

max at index 0 = 3;
max at index 1 = 3(product will be -3);
max at index 2 = 3(product will be -12);

but we can see that the maximum product will be **4** if we traverse from the right side of the array.

max at index 2 = 4;
max at index 1 = 4(product will be -4);
max at index 0 = 4(product will be -12);

hence , when we traverse from the last also it will rectify the mistake and give us the correct answer as **4**.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int maxProduct(int[] nums) {
        int curr = 1;
        int i , j , len = nums.length;
        int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        for(i = 0 ; i < len ; i++){
            curr *= nums[i];
            if(curr > max){
                max = curr;
            }
            if(curr == 0){
                curr = 1;
            }
        }
        curr = 1;
        for(j = len - 1 ; j >= 0 ; j--){
            curr *= nums[j];
            if(curr > max){
                max = curr;
            }
            if(curr == 0){
                curr = 1;
            }
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

