# Intuition
The SummaryRanges class is used to keep track of a set of intervals and provide methods to add new numbers to the set and retrieve the current set of intervals. The class uses a vector to store the intervals, where each interval is represented by a vector containing the start and end values of the interval.

The addNum() method is used to add a new number to the set of intervals. It first initializes the start and end values of the new interval to the given value. It then iterates through the existing intervals and checks if the new interval overlaps with any of them. If it does, it updates the start and end values of the new interval to include the overlapping intervals, and removes those intervals from the set. If the new interval does not overlap with any existing intervals, it is inserted into the set in the appropriate position.

The getIntervals() method simply returns the current set of intervals.

Overall, the SummaryRanges class is useful for keeping track of a set of intervals and easily adding new numbers to the set while maintaining the integrity of the intervals.
# Approach
1. Initialize an empty list, intervals, to store the disjoint intervals.
2. Implement the addNum(int value) function:
    - Initialize a variable, start, to the value.
    - Initialize a variable, end, to the value.
    - Iterate through the intervals list:
        - If the value is within any of the intervals, return.
        - If the value is one less than the start of an interval, update the start of that interval to be the value.
        - If the value is one more than the end of an interval, update the end of that interval to be the value.
        - If the value is between two intervals, insert a new interval with start and end equal to the value.
3. Implement the getIntervals() function:
    - Sort the intervals list by the start of each interval.
    - Return the intervals list as a 2D array.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
 $$O(n)$$ :
The time complexity of the addNum function is O(n) because in the worst case, the function needs to iterate through all the intervals in the intervals vector to check for overlapping intervals, and the space complexity is O(n) as well, because the size of the intervals vector will grow as new intervals are added.

- Space complexity:
 $$O(1)$$ :
space complexity of O(1) because it simply returns a reference to the intervals vector without any additional processing.

# Code
```
// C++
class SummaryRanges {
    vector<vector<int>> intervals;

public:
    SummaryRanges() {}

    void addNum(int value) {
        int start = value, end = value;
        auto it = intervals.begin();
        while (it != intervals.end()) {
            if (it->at(1) + 1 < start) {
                ++it;
                continue;
            }
            if (it->at(0) - 1 > end) break;
            start = min(start, it->at(0));
            end = max(end, it->at(1));
            it = intervals.erase(it);
        }
        intervals.insert(it, {start, end});
    }

    vector<vector<int>> getIntervals() {
        return intervals;
    }
};


