# Intuition
At every `getIntervals` query we have to generate and send the interval in sorted order. So, we should keep our data in the sorted order, which data-structure can help us here?
Yes, you are right, it's `set` data-structure.

# Approach
Our answer is going to to be nothing but vector of vector of 2 elements (or can say, vector of pair), i.e., `[{s1,e1}, {s2,s2}, {s3,e3}]` we don't have to care about elements in between `s` and `e`.

So, at every `getIntervals` query we have to traverse the `set` and updated the answer.

Now, if our `ans` is empty we have to create a new "range" with `s = x` and `e = x` i.e., `ans.push_back({x,x})`

If the `e` of the last pair of the `ans` is equals to `x - 1` then we have got one more element for our last pair. So, we just update the `e` of the last pair of the `ans`. i.e., `ans.back().back() = x`.
If not so, then we again have to create a new "range" with `s = x` and `e = x`.

where `x` is the current set element.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/88b3a326-d8c4-4c44-badc-75fa0d285310_1674927940.6129165.png)



# Code
```
class SummaryRanges {
public:
    set<int> st;

    SummaryRanges() {}

    void addNum(int value) {
        st.emplace(value);
    }

    vector<vector<int>> getIntervals() {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        for(auto x:st){
            if(ans.size() && ans.back().back()+1 == x) ans.back().back() = x;
            else ans.push_back({x,x});
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

