# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use a TreeMap to store intervals, where the key is the start of an interval and the value is the end. A TreeMap will naturally sort all the keys (beginning of the intervals) in ascending order.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(log(N))$$ for addNum, $$O(N)$$ for getIntervals.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class SummaryRanges {
  TreeMap<Integer, Integer> map;

  public SummaryRanges() {
    map = new TreeMap<>();
  }

  public void addNum(int value) {
    var f = map.floorEntry(value);
    var c = map.ceilingEntry(value);

    // Case: value is part of an existing interval, do nothing.
    if ((f != null && value >= f.getKey() && value <= f.getValue())
        || (c != null && value >= c.getKey() && value <= c.getValue()))
      return;

    // Case: value is not part of any existing interval, create a new interval.
    if ((f == null || value - f.getValue() > 1)
        && (c == null || c.getKey() - value > 1)) {
      map.put(value, value);
      return;
    }
    // Case: value must be merged with both the prior and subsequent intervals.
    if (f != null && value - f.getValue() == 1
        && c != null && c.getKey() - value == 1) {
      map.put(f.getKey(), c.getValue());
      map.remove(c.getKey());
      return;
    }
    // Case: value must be merged with only the prior interval.
    if (f != null && value - f.getValue() == 1) {
      map.put(f.getKey(), value);
    } else {
      // Case: value must be merged with only the subsequent interval.
      map.put(value, c.getValue());
      map.remove(c.getKey());
    }
  }

  public int[][] getIntervals() {
    var res = new int[map.size()][2];
    var i = 0;

    for (var entry : map.entrySet()) {
      res[i][0] = entry.getKey();
      res[i++][1] = entry.getValue();
    }
    return res;
  }
}
```

