solutions.content:
Basic idea: construct BST of nodes with Interval as attribute.

The complex part is addNum method.

Four cases in total (assume n is current root node to add val):

1. val < n.intv.start - 1: add to left subtree
2. val == n.intv.start - 1: 
    2.1. merge n with the right most node in left subtree;
    2.2.merge n with val
3. val == n.intv.end + 1:
    3.1. merge n with the left most node in right subtree;
    3.2.merge n with val
4. val > n.intv.end + 1: add to right subtree

```
class SummaryRanges {
	private class TreeNode {
		Interval intv;
		TreeNode left, right;
		public TreeNode(Interval i) {
			intv = i;
		}
	}

	TreeNode root;

    /** Initialize your data structure here. */
    public SummaryRanges() {
        root = null;
    }

    public void addNum(int val) {
    	root = addNum(root, val);
    }

    private TreeNode addNum(TreeNode n, int val) {
    	if (n == null) {
    		n = new TreeNode(new Interval(val, val));
    		return n;
    	}
    	if (val < n.intv.start - 1) {
    		n.left = addNum(n.left, val);
    	}
    	else if (val == n.intv.start - 1) {
    		TreeNode rightMost = n.left, rightMostPrev = n;
    		while (rightMost != null && rightMost.right != null) {
    			rightMostPrev = rightMost;
    			rightMost = rightMost.right;
    		}
    		if (rightMost != null && rightMost.intv.end + 1 == val) {
    			n.intv.start = rightMost.intv.start;
    			if (rightMostPrev != n) {
    				rightMostPrev.right = rightMost.left;
