Looking at the examples we can see its split into three general cases when adding a new number
1. create new interval
2. merge two intervals
3. add number to existing interval

Looking at the three cases, when does each happen?

1. when 2 and 3 are **both** not met
2. when the number is within one of the end **and** start of two **consecutive** intervals
3. when the number is within one of a start **or** end of only **one** existing interval

The only issue is now dealing with edge cases of when found interval is begin or end.

Use a ordered tree structure to make modification and lookup `O(lg(sz(M_n))) ∈ O(lg(calls to addNum))` aswell as `upper_bound ∈ O(lg(sz(M_n)))`, or in general terms `addNum ∈ O(nlg(n))` for a series of`n` calls. Of course `getIntervals ∈ O(n * m)` for a series of `n` and `m` calls to `getIntervals` and `addNum` respectively .
```
class SummaryRanges
{

  public:

    map<int,int> M_p;

    void addNum(int v)
    {
        auto iter = M_p.upper_bound(v);

        const auto r_diff = iter == end(M_p)
            ? 2
            : iter->first - v;
        const auto l_diff = iter == begin(M_p)
            ? 2
            : v - prev(iter)->second;

        if (r_diff > 1 && l_diff > 1)
        {
            // insert new
            M_p[v] = v;
        }
        else if (r_diff == 1 && l_diff == 1)
        {
            // delete right and make that end left end
            prev(iter)->second = iter->second;
            M_p.erase(iter);
        }
        else if (r_diff == 1)
        {
            // update beginning of right
            M_p[v] = iter->second;
            M_p.erase(iter);
        }
        else if (l_diff == 1)
        {
            // update beginning of left
            prev(iter)->second = v;
        }
    }

    vector<vector<int>> getIntervals()
    {
        vector<vector<int>> v;

        for (const auto& [a,b] : M_p)
        {
            v.push_back({a,b});
        }

        return v;
    }

};
```

