**So Ladies n Gentlemen without any further due let's start,**
` What Question is saying, given the array points, return the minimum number of arrows that must be shot to burst all balloons`.


**Approach Explained:**

**Summary :**
* Sort intervals/pairs in increasing order of the end position
* Finding the common area of current interval with start and end,if they intersect....(for example { [1,6] , [2,8] } these intervals intersect common area is [2,6])
* Else if no common area update start and end to current interval and increment arrow count

**Explained:**
`Greedy algorithm:`

* An arrow shoots through multiple intervals, all of which are coincident. We try to stack the overlapping intervals together and give a jump.
* To facilitate identifying coincidence in a single traversal, we sort in ascending order on the right

To, solve this problem first of all what we do is **sort the Array points**. Let's say we have these point's array **[[10,16],[2,8],[1,6],[7,12]]**. And we will solve this array based on the end index. So, by doing that what will happen with our Array is **[1,6]** will come first then **[2,8]** will come, third one is **[7,12]** & last is from **[10,16]**.
So, these are the **4 values x-coordinates** are given like this. Let me show you in diagram :

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6a666e3d-d0b1-4410-88aa-4b36fb09c3ad_1642043072.2629914.png)


Now, for **bursting these Ballons** 1st one we need one shot anywhere **1 to 6 including these edges**. So, what we will do is we will **greedly sort** over here at the end of **[6]**. So, if we shot it, the baloon burst and along with another one **[2,8]** will burst as well with only **1 arrow.**
As, we have **burst 2 ballons** and 2 more left. So, again if we shot it over **[12]** then it will burst **[10,16] as well**.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a4cea92e-f1f7-4f5d-9444-0076308f9367_1642043545.1509588.png)


