# Approach
Greedy approach
# Steps:
1. Sort intervals/pairs in increasing order of the end position
2. Finding the common area of current interval with start and end,if they intersect....(for example { [1,6] , [2,8] } these intervals intersect common area is [2,6])
3. If no common area update start and end to current interval and increment arrow count
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(nlogn)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMinArrowShots(vector<vector<int>>& v) {
        sort(v.begin(),v.end()); //sort the array
        int l=v[0][0];
        int r=v[0][1],cnt=1;
        for(int i=1;i<v.size();i++){
           if(v[i][0]<=r){
              r=min(r,v[i][1]); //ending value of common interval
              l=max(l,v[i][0]); // starting value of common interval
           }
           else{
               cnt++; // no common interval hence increment the count
               l=v[i][0]; //update the start value of common interval by start value of current index.
               r=v[i][1];  //update the ending point of common interval by ending value of current index.
           }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
};

