# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We have to find **common range** among the balloons. The problem can be solved in many ways but we have to find the **efficient** solution.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can start by **sorting** the array with respect to its **end position** so that it will be easy to find the range. 

Follow the code below to understand the solution.

            **If this solution helped you, give it an up-vote to help others** 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlogn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findMinArrowShots(int[][] points) {

        //Sort the array with respect to end position i.e. points[i][1].
        //We will use lambda expression to customize the sorting.
         Arrays.sort(points, (a,b) -> Integer.compare(a[1],b[1]));

        //Initialize arrow count from 1 because at least 1 arrow is needed.
        int arrowCount = 1;
        int previous = 0;

        for(int current = 0; current < points.length; current++)
        {
            // If the start position of current balloon is after the end
            // position of previous balloon then increment arrow counter.
            if(points[current][0] > points[previous][1])
            {
                arrowCount++;
                // Update the index of the previously burst balloon
                previous = current;
            }

        }

        //Finally return the arrow count.

        return arrowCount;         

    }
}
```

