solutions.content:
Another problem in the family of overlapping intervals, clearly, and as such it should be solved.

First of all I sorted the array by closing intervals first and opening intervals second, using the helper function `comp`; turns out just sorting by closing intervals was enough, but I did not see much of a change saving the conditional in the function.

Also, be sure to pass the parameters as references for your comparing function: I was about to forget it (again 🤦‍♂️ ) and man if it hit the performance!

Then I declared a few helper variables:
* `len` will store the lenght of the input variable;
* `res` will be initialised to be `= len`, since we will assume that initially you will need `len` arrows and then decrease for each overlap spotted;
* `lmt` stores up to where we are considering checking for overlaps - initialised with the closing value of the very first element of the (now sorted) input.

We will then loop through all the other elements (ie: starting from the second) and check if the opening time of the current interval is `> lmt`:
* if so, we update `lmt` to the closing (notice!) time of the current one;
* otherwise, we found an overlap and can decrease `res` by `1`.

If you assume this starting input:

```cpp
[[10,16],[2,8],[1,6],[7,12],[3,4],[12,16],[9,12],[9,11],[3,7],[4,9],[15,16],[1,3],[6,8]]
// res == 13: the initial length of the input
```

You will have the array sorted something like this:

```cpp
{1, 3}, {3, 4}, {1, 6}, {3, 7}, {6, 8}, {2, 8}, {4, 9}, {9, 11}, {9, 12}, {7, 12}, {15, 16}, {12, 16}, {10, 16}
// lmt == 3
// res == 13
```

`lmt` is initially going to be set to `3`, shooting there you will only take down the first balloon, then you will update it to `4`, take down the balloons from the second to the fourth (so you will have to decrease `res` by `2`), update `lmt` and so on.

Notice **we do not actully remove items from the array**, as it would be rather expensive, while iterating is enough; I just removed them for display convenience:

```cpp
// hit the first, it goes down alone and we update lmt
{3, 4}, {1, 6}, {3, 7}, {6, 8}, {2, 8}, {4, 9}, {9, 11}, {9, 12}, {7, 12}, {15, 16}, {12, 16}, {10, 16}
// lmt == 4
// res == 13

// hit the next 3 with one arrow, res goes down by 2 and we update lmt
{6, 8}, {2, 8}, {4, 9}, {9, 11}, {9, 12}, {7, 12}, {15, 16}, {12, 16}, {10, 16}
// lmt == 8
// res == 11

// ...
// try to execute all the intermediate steps on your own and you should end up like this:

// last step: one last arrow to down 3 - notice that {10, 16} might have been downed before, for example
// if you had sorted by starting time, but it really does not change the ultimate result
{15, 16}, {12, 16}, {10, 16}
// lmt == 16
// res == 6

// final step
// lmt == 16
// res == 4
```

Once done, we can return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
static auto comp = [](auto &a, auto &b){return a[1] != b[1] ? a[1] < b[1] : a[0] > b[0];};

class Solution {
public:
    int findMinArrowShots(vector<vector<int>>& pts) {
        // edge case out
        if (!pts.size()) return 0;
        // sorting by ending time first, then starting time
        sort(begin(pts), end(pts), comp);
        // support variables
        int len = pts.size(), res = len, lmt = pts[0][1];
        // finding all the overlaps
        for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) {
            // overlap not found
			if (lmt < pts[i][0]) lmt = pts[i][1];
			// overlap found
            else res--;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

