solutions.content:
### Intuition
So this problem is simple classic `overlapping intervals` problem but intervals come in balloons and overlapping come in shooting area where you have to shoot at to hit your targets which are the balloons. 

Enough talking lets visualize the problem with my high art skills:
We will take our first testcase where points = [ [10,16] , [2,8] , [1,6] , [7,12] ]
Then We will sort them to get [ [1,6] , [2,8] , [7,12] , [10,16] ]
![photo_٢٠٢٣-٠١-٢٢_٠٩-١٦-٣٧.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/69b425d8-bd91-49fa-ac41-ca4f0b9ab858_1674372816.3341389.jpeg)
So as we can painfully see our overlapping areas are 3 areas:
-First area is between **first & second ballon**.
-Second area is between **second & third ballon**.
-Third area is between **third & fourth ballon**.

We need to use **minimum number of arrows** to **burst all ballons**, so if we shot at first area we will burst first & second ballon, if in second area we will burst second & third ballon and if in third area we will burst third & fourth ballon.
That's it, We got all of our targets with **3 arrows**, But wait a minute We could have got all of our targets with only **2 arrows** and that's by shooting at first area and third area only, so now we understand that we don't use or count every **overlapping area**, but just the ones necessary to hit our targets with minimum shots.

So if you already bursted a ballon **ignore it** and **focus on next coming one** and here it's clear that we will take a ***Greedy*** Approach where we focus only on our current step to get least shots and highest output.

### Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We will sort the ballons by `x.end` where -> `points[ i ] = [ x.start ,  x.end ]`.

So We will use what we can call **two pointers** in this Greedy approach, where first pointer will be pointing at our current ballon and next pointer will be moving and pointing on next ballons to find a ballon that doesn't share an overlapping area with our current ballon.

At this point when we find that **non-overlapping ballon** we will move our current ballon's pointer to point at the **non-overlapping ballon.**

At every time we move our current ballon's pointer we will increase the **number of arrows we shot**, until we return the number of all **used arrows**.
*We will use a `for loop` for the process above.
*Initail value for number of **used arrows** is one, and it is one because we start counting after shooting first ballon.

### C++
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMinArrowShots(vector<vector<int>>& points) {
        sort(points.begin(), points.end(), [](vector<int>& x, vector<int>& y) {
            return x[1] < y[1];
        });

        int usedArrows = 1;
        for (int curr = 0, next = 1; next < points.size(); next++) {
            if (points[curr][1] < points[next][0]) {
                curr = next;
                usedArrows++;
            }
        }

        return usedArrows;
    }
};
```
