# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
By seeing the problem we get the idea of finding out the balloons that share some common interval or whose intersection is not NULL , So we try to find out the balloons sharing co-ordinates in same range.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

**Step 1:** We sort the given points vector in increasing order of their starting points.

**Step 2:** We maintain a ```maxStart``` and ```minEnd``` variable.
The logic behind these variables is that whenever we find two ranges having an Intersection then our valid range in which the arrow will be able to burst the balloons decreases (i.e. we have to take the Intersection of the ranges.)

**Step 3:** Now we check that the starting point of the current balloon lies within our desired range or not. 

* If it does we just update the range by taking the Intersection and updating the variables. 
* If it doesn't we update the number of arrows and start with new range. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(NlogN)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMinArrowShots(vector<vector<int>>& points) {

        if(points.size()==1)
        return 1;

        sort(points.begin(),points.end());
        int ans = 1, minEnd = points[0][1], maxStart = points[0][0];

        for(int i=1;i<points.size();i++)
        {
            if(points[i][0]>=minStart && points[i][0]<=minEnd)
            {
                maxStart = max(maxStart,points[i][0]);
                minEnd = min(minEnd,points[i][1]);
            }

            else
            {
                ans++;
                maxStart = points[i][0];
                minEnd = points[i][1];
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
