# Intuition
Say, there are 3 balloons A, B and C

- A and B overlap by some degree
- B and C overlap by some degree
- A and C do not overlap
- middle point of every balloon do not overlap

So worst case here would be that you fire at the center and use 3 arrows

Best case would be 2 arrows if u pop A and B and use 1 arrow for C

Now,

if number of balloons which overlaps with A is 1
and number of balloons which overlaps with B but not A becomes 10000

then also you would need 2 arrows whether you take out B with A or use 1 arrow for A and 1 for B with the overlapped balloons.

If you take out B with A then the remaining overlapped balloons will still continue to overlap each other and u can shoot them all using 1 arrow.

In any case you are going to get minimum arrows if you take out all the balloons which overlap a certain balloon with a single arrow

# Approach
We need an endpoint which will help in deciding whether the next balloon is overlapped with the current one or not.

We also need balloons to be sorted with respect to endpoint so that we can apply the above operation in sequence and sorting wrt endpoint will guarantee that the next balloon is overlapping the endpoint of the placeholder.

So after sorting, we take first balloon as our placeholder and fire an arrow at its end point, then we check whether the next balloon has its starting point <= the placeholder's ending points

if true then the arrow we fired will take it out so we go to the next balloon and check its starting point with the placeholder and so on.

if false then we increment our answer and make the new balloon our placeholder and continue.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMinArrowShots(vector<vector<int>>& points) {
        sort(points.begin(), points.end(), [](vector<int>& a, vector<int>& b) -> bool {
            return a[1] == b[1] ? a[0] < b[0] : a[1] < b[1];
        });

        int prev = points[0][1], ans = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i < points.size(); i++) {
            if (points[i][0] > prev) prev = points[i][1], ans++;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(nlogn)$$

