# Intuition
If we observe the inputs carefully, we can see that if we arrange the points in sorted order based on the ending position, we can make sure that all the balloons having starting position lesser than the ending position can be burst in one shot. Please look into the image below.
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ed78dc4b-3141-42c6-822e-a1f0943c4b0a_1672897902.5367217.png)


# Approach
- check for edge cases always
- intialize the integer variables countArrows and prevIndex to keep track of the values
- sort the points based on the ending positions
- iterate over the points and check whether the starting position is exceeding the previous ending position
- return countArrows

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N), where N is the length of points array

- Space complexity: O(1) as only using the constant space

**Please Upvote If this solution helps you to learn something. Thanks in advance.**

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findMinArrowShots(int[][] points) {
        // edge cases
        if(points == null || points.length == 0){
            return 0;
        }

        // intialization
        int countArrows = 0;
        int prevIndex = 0;

        // sort the points based on the ending position
        Arrays.sort(points, (a, b)->(Integer.compare(a[1], b[1])));

        // iterate over the points
        for(int index = 0;index < points.length;index++){
            // when initially countArrows is zero or
            // starting position of current balloon is greater
            // than the ending position of the previous group
            if(countArrows == 0 || points[index][0] > points[prevIndex][1]){
                countArrows++;
                prevIndex = index;
            }
        }

        return countArrows;
    }
}


