# Intuition
1. Maintain the intersecting area covered by balloons while iterating the balloons

2. If current balloon has no intersecting area with previous common area then increase asnwer and the current balloon area will be the new intersecting area

- Eg: current common area = [2,6]
Current balloon area = [3,7] , then common area = intersecting area = [3,6]

- Eg: current common area = [2,6]
Current balloon area = [7,9] , then new common area = [7,9] and increase the answer by 1 
# Approach
1. Sort all balloons to get start points in ascending order(start points will be sorted first and if start points are equal , then end points will be sorted) 

2. Check current intersecting area endpoint with current balloon area startpoint .
- If $$(xstart)curr$$ <=$$(xend)common$$ then areas are intersecting

- else we need 1 more arrow to burst this balloon and intersecting area will be the current balloon area

(Initial answer is set to 1 as we need a minimum of 1 arrow to burst a balloon and initial area is taken as area of first balloon)


# Complexity
- Time complexity : $$O(nlogn)$$

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

