# Approach
1. First, check if the size of the input array points is 1. If it is, return 1 since only one balloon needs to be shot.
2. Sort the array points based on the second element of each subarray
3. Initialize a variable count to 1 and a variable prevElement to the second element of the first subarray of points.
4. Iterate through the points array starting from the second element. For each iteration:
    - If prevElement is greater than or equal to the first element of the current subarray, continue to the next iteration.
    - Otherwise, increment count by 1 and set prevElement to the second element of the current subarray.  
1. Return count.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(nlogn)**  // where n is the size of vector
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: **O(1)**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Java Code
```
class Solution {
    public static int sortCol(int[] v1, int[] v2) {
        return v1[1] - v2[1];
    }

    public int findMinArrowShots(int[][] points) {
        if(points.length == 1)
            return 1;
        int row = points.length;
        int count = 1;
        Arrays.sort(points, Comparator.comparingInt(v -> v[1]));
        int prevElement = points[0][1];
        for(int i = 1; i < row; i++){
            if(prevElement >= points[i][0]){
                continue;
            }
            else{ 
                count++;
                prevElement = points[i][1];
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

